      </solution>
    </example>

    <p> Now let's formalize the classification of critical points like we did in the last example using the first derivative. </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-first-derivative-test">
      <title>First Derivative Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be differentiable on an interval around <m>c</m> and suppose <m>f'(c)=0</m>.
        </p>
        <ul> 
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x)&gt;0</m> for <m>x&lt;c</m> and <m>f'(x)&lt;0</m> for <m>x&gt;c</m>,
              then <m>x=c</m> is a local maximum.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x)&lt;0</m> for <m>x&lt;c</m> and <m>f'(x)&gt;0</m> for <m>x&gt;c</m>,
              then <m>x=c</m> is a local minimum.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f'(x)</m> has the same sign on both sides of <m>c</m>,
              then <m>x=c</m> is neither a local maximum nor a local minimum.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>

  <p>So with only the first derivative, we can determine where a function is increasing or decreasing and classify critical points as local maxima, minima, or neither. 
    However, there are other features of the graph that we can analyze using the second derivative. </p>


  <subsection xml:id="ssec-concavity">
    <title>Concavity and Inflection Points</title>

    <p>
      Increasing and decreasing behavior describes whether the graph rises or falls.
      Concavity describes how the graph bends.
    </p> 

    <definition xml:id="def-concavity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A graph is <term>concave up</term> when it looks like a smile, the curve is bending upwards. The graph is <term>concave down</term>
      when it looks like a frown, the curve is bending downwards.
      An <term>inflection point</term> is a point where the concavity changes.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark xml:id="rem-concavity-visual">
      <p>  Concavity is independent of increasing/decreasing behavior. A graph can be increasing and concave down at the same time, for example. 
        Here are some examples of graphs with different combinations of increasing/decreasing and concavity.
      </p> 


