          To find horizontal asymptotes, we compute limits as <m>x\to\pm\infty</m>. 
          We can use dominant term analysis to find that 
          
          <me>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to\pm\infty} f(x) \approx \lim_{x\to\pm\infty} \dfrac{x^{2/3}}{x^2} = \lim_{x\to\pm\infty} x^{-4/3} = 0</me> 
          
          so there is a horizontal asymptote at <m>y=0</m>. 
        </p> 
        <p> (b) To find critical points, we first compute the derivative using the quotient rule: </p>
        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
            f'(x) &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{(x^{2/3})'(x-1)^2 - x^{2/3}((x-1)^2)'}{(x-1)^4} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{\frac{2}{3}x^{-1/3}(x-1)^2 - x^{2/3}\cdot 2(x-1)}{(x-1)^4} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{\frac{2}{3}x^{-1/3}(x-1) - 2x^{2/3}}{(x-1)^3} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{2x^{-1/3}(x-1) - 6x^{2/3}}{3(x-1)^3}\\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{2x^{-1/3}(x-1) - 6x^{2/3}}{3(x-1)^3} \cdot \frac{x^{1/3}}{x^{1/3}} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{2(x-1) - 6x}{3x^{1/3}(x-1)^3} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-4x-2}{3x^{1/3}(x-1)^3}
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          The critical points occur where <m>f'(x)=0</m> or where <m>f'(x)</m> is undefined (while <m>f</m> is defined). 
          Since the denominator is zero at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=1</m>, we know <m>x=0</m> is a critical point (but <m>x=1</m> is not, since <m>f</m> is undefined there). 
          We also set the numerator equal to zero and solve for <m>x</m> to find other critical points:
          <me>
            -4x-2=0 \implies x=-\frac{1}{2}.
          </me>
          So the critical points are at <m>x=-\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>x=0</m>.
        </p>
        <p> 
          To determine where <m>f</m> is increasing or decreasing, we can use the test point method to check the sign of <m>f'(x)</m> in each
