  <exercises xml:id="exercises-curve-sketching-1">
    <title>Practice / Study Problems</title>

  


  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Some True/False Problems</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Determine whether each statement is true or false and briefly justify your reasoning.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-01">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f'(x)&gt;0</m> for all <m>x</m> in an interval <m>(a,b)</m>, then <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>(a,b)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>True.</em> This is exactly the Increasing/Decreasing Test.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-02">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f'(3)=0</m>, then <m>f</m> has a local maximum or a local minimum at <m>x=3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>False.</em> A critical point can be neither. For example, consider <m>f(x)=x^3</m> at <m>x=0</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

<!--
    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-04">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f'(x)</m> changes sign from positive to negative at <m>x=2</m>, then <m>f</m> has a local minimum at <m>x=2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>False.</em> Positive to negative indicates a local maximum by the First Derivative Test.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
-->

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-05">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f'(x)</m> changes sign from negative to positive at <m>x=2</m>, then <m>f</m> has a local minimum at <m>x=2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>True.</em> This is the First Derivative Test for a local minimum.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>


    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-07">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f''(x)&gt;0</m> on an interval, then the slopes of <m>f</m> are increasing on that interval.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>True.</em> <m>f''(x)&gt;0</m> means <m>f'(x)</m> is increasing.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-08">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is increasing on an interval, then it must be concave up on that interval.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>False.</em> A function can be increasing and concave down.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-09">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is concave down on an interval, then <m>f'(x)</m> is decreasing on that interval.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>True.</em> Concave down means <m>f''(x)&lt;0</m>, so <m>f'(x)</m> decreases.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-10">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f''(5)=0</m>, then <m>(5,f(5))</m> must be an inflection point.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>False.</em> You also need <m>f''</m> to change sign at <m>x=5</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-11">
      <statement>
        <p>
          It is possible for <m>f</m> to have an inflection point at <m>x=-1</m> even if <m>f'(-1)=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>True.</em> Inflection points concern concavity; the slope can be zero there.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-12">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f''(x)</m> is undefined at <m>x=4</m>, then <m>x=4</m> cannot be an inflection point.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>False.</em> An inflection point can occur where <m>f''</m> is undefined, as long as concavity changes and <m>f</m> is defined.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="tf-curve1-13">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the graph of <m>f</m> below. On this graph <m>f'(2) \gt f''(2)</m>.
        </p> 

 <image width="60%">
<shortdescription>
A coordinate plane showing a curve labeled f(x). 
The curve is increasing from left to right and gradually flattening, 
meaning its slope is positive but decreasing as x increases. 
The graph bends downward, indicating it is concave down. A solid point is marked on the curve directly above x equals 2, 
with a dashed vertical line dropping from the point to the x-axis at 2. 
</shortdescription>

    <latex-image><![CDATA[

\begin{tikzpicture}
		\draw[->] (-.5, 0) -- (4.5,0);
		\draw[->] (0,-.5) -- (0,2.5);
		\draw plot[domain=.2:4, smooth] (\x, {(\x)^0.5});
		\draw[dashed] (2, {2^0.5}) node {$\bullet$} -- (2,-4pt) node[below] {$2$}; 
		\draw (1,2) node {$f(x)$};
	\end{tikzpicture}

      ]]></latex-image>
  </image>        

      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p><em>True.</em> The slope at <m>x=2</m> is positive (the curve is increasing), so therefore <m>f'(2) \gt 0</m>.
          The concavity is downward (the curve is bending down), so <m>f''(2) \lt 0</m>. Therefore, <m>f'(2) \gt f''(2)</m>.</p>
      </solution>
      
    </exercise>



   

